Event Summary
Khanun Sirapop, a political activist in Thailand, went on hunger strike from 21 February 2025 until 16 March 2025, in protest of his ongoing detention and the denial of bail. He was sentenced under the royal defamation law on 25 March 2024 to two years in prison for a speech he made at a rally in November 2020, where he allegedly criticized the monarchy. Despite multiple bail applications, all of which have been denied, Khanun’s health is rapidly deteriorating. He has lost significant weight and is experiencing serious health issues, yet the authorities did not granted him proper medical care. This case highlights continuing concerns about political repression and restrictions on fundamental freedoms in Thailand.
&nbsp;

Event Summary


In April 2025, the Timor-Leste Government, through the Centro Nacional Chega Instituto Publiku (CNC), appointed various civil society actors—including NGOs, resistance groups from the Indonesian occupation era, veterans, and foundations operating in Timor-Leste—as members of the taskforce group known as the &#8220;Timorese Reconciliation Process&#8221; (PRT). This group was formed to assist the CNC in organizing and facilitating reconciliation efforts for those involved in political conflicts from 1974 to 1999.




Notable civil society actors invited to join the taskforce include the HAK Foundation, RENETIL, ACBIT, and others. On 4 April 2025, the taskforce held a reconciliation dialogue in Liquica Municipality, bringing together victims of the Liquica massacre and some of its perpetrators. This indicates an improvement in collaborations between government and civil society.


&nbsp;
&nbsp;

Event Summary
On 15 April 2025, the Cabinet for Civil Society (GASC), under the office of Timor-Leste&#8217;s Deputy Prime Minister, announced the first list of 77 recipients in the &#8220;Religious Confessions and Congregations&#8221; category, selected to receive funding based on their submitted proposals. Further results for the &#8220;NGOs, Foundations, and Associations&#8221; category are expected by late April or early May 2025. This follows an open call for proposals issued by GASC in December 2024, inviting NGOs, CBOs, Foundations, Associations, and religious groups to apply for funding to support their strategic activities, such as construction, governance, and community training. GASC aims to ensure equitable access to funds, focusing on areas like civic education, governance, and institutional empowerment within Community of Portuguese Language Countries (CPLP) and Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) networks. GASC annually provides $6 million in grants to 145 civil society organizations. This initiative reflects ongoing support for strengthening civil society in Timor-Leste.
&nbsp;

Event Summary



Durante la inauguración de una obra pública, el presidente de la República se refirió a la marcha de maestros y trabajadores de la construcción,  llevada a cabo el 4 de abril de 2025 en protesta contra de las reformas a la Caja de Seguro Social. En su discurso, el mandatario calificó a estos grupos de comunistas. 
Expresó lo siguiente:
«Que vayan a trabajar, y si no les gusta Panamá que se vayan para Venezuela, Cuba, Nicaragua o dondequiera, pero que no vengan aquí a pescar en la anarquía para cambiar un sistema que es democrático que nos interesa a todos».
«Ellos pescan en la anarquía y eso es lo que vienen haciendo fracaso tras fracaso porque lo de ayer fue gran fracaso a nivel nacional. Vi todas las fotos de estas benditas huelgas de todos estos comunistas y son ellos con ellos».
“Ellos conspiran con plata ajena y ya no van a tener plata”
&nbsp;
También se refirió  a la Universidad de Panamá, como “guarida de terroristas” , luego de las protestas y cierres de calles realizadas por estudiantes de esta casa de estudio.
&nbsp;
